Video Streaming & MP4 Optimization — Practical Developer Notes
----------------------------------------------------------------

1. How Video Streaming Works on the Web

Most modern web apps use the HTML5 <video> player.

Example:

<video src="https://signed-url/video.mp4" controls></video>

The browser does not download the full video first.
Instead it uses HTTP Range Requests.

Example request:

Range: bytes=0-1048575

Server response:

Status: 206 Partial Content
Accept-Ranges: bytes
Content-Range: bytes 0-1048575/120000000

Meaning:

Browser requested only a portion of the file
↓
Server returned that portion
↓
Video starts playing

This is called:

Progressive streaming

2. Progressive Streaming vs True Streaming
Progressive Streaming (Most common)
Browser downloads small parts of the file
↓
Playback begins
↓
More chunks are downloaded while watching

Used by:

HTML5 <video>

Cloudflare R2

AWS S3

normal MP4 delivery

Advantages:

Simple architecture

Works with signed URLs

No complex encoding pipeline

True Streaming (HLS / DASH)

Used by:

Netflix

YouTube

OTT platforms

Structure:

video.m3u8
segment1.ts
segment2.ts
segment3.ts

Advantages:

Adaptive quality

optimized for slow networks

Disadvantages:

requires encoding pipeline

complicated

not easy with signed URLs

3. Why Videos Sometimes Load Slowly

MP4 files contain metadata called the "moov atom".

Two possible structures exist.

Bad Structure (Default MP4)
[video data...............................]
[moov metadata]

Problem:

Browser cannot start playback
until it finds metadata

So it may download a large part of the file first.

Result:

slow startup
Optimized Structure (Fast Start)
[moov metadata]
[video data...............................]

Now browser can:

read metadata immediately
↓
start playback instantly
4. What MP4 Fast Start Does

Fast Start moves metadata to the beginning.

FFmpeg command:

ffmpeg -i input.mp4 -c copy -movflags +faststart output.mp4

Explanation:

-c copy

means:

no re-encoding
no quality loss
very fast processing
-movflags +faststart

moves the metadata to the start of the file.

5. When Fast Start Is Useful

Fast Start improves:

video startup time

It does NOT change:

video quality
video bitrate
video streaming mechanism

So:

Feature	Effect
Video start speed	Faster
Streaming method	Same
File size	Same
Video quality	Same
6. Cloudflare R2 Video Streaming Behavior

Cloudflare R2 behaves like S3 object storage.

Important characteristics:

supports Range requests

Meaning:

Accept-Ranges: bytes

So browsers automatically do:

progressive streaming

Even without any extra configuration.

7. Signed URL Architecture for Private Videos

Private platforms cannot expose public URLs.

Solution:

signed URLs

Example:

https://r2-bucket/video.mp4?X-Amz-Algorithm=...

Properties:

temporary access
secure
no authentication required on CDN

Common in:

course platforms

paid video content

private apps

8. Why HLS Was Not Suitable Here

HLS requires many segment requests.

Example:

playlist.m3u8
segment_1.ts
segment_2.ts
segment_3.ts

Problem with signed URLs:

each segment would require a signed URL

Which becomes extremely complex.

So architecture chosen:

Signed URL + Progressive MP4

This is simple and scalable.

9. Backend Processing Pipeline for Large Videos

Uploading large videos requires careful memory management.

Bad approach:

upload file → keep in memory → process

This causes:

high RAM usage
server crashes
Correct Approach (Disk + Streams)

Pipeline used:

Upload video
↓
save to temp file
↓
run FFmpeg optimization
↓
stream upload to storage
↓
delete temp files

Architecture:

multer.diskStorage
↓
FFmpeg
↓
createReadStream
↓
uploadStreamToR2

Advantages:

low RAM usage
handles large files
safe for production
10. Why Streaming Uploads Matter

Instead of:

uploadBufferToR2(buffer)

Use:

uploadStreamToR2(stream)

Example:

new PutObjectCommand({
  Bucket,
  Key,
  Body: stream
})

Benefits:

no large memory allocation
supports 500MB+ uploads
11. Safe Stream Download Pattern

When downloading files from cloud storage:

Bad:

stream.pipe(writeStream)

Better:

await pipeline(stream, fs.createWriteStream(path))

Advantages:

waits for completion
handles errors
avoids corrupted files
12. Temp File Processing Strategy

Large files must be processed in a temporary directory.

Example:

/tmp/video-processing/

Workflow:

write input file
↓
run FFmpeg
↓
generate optimized file
↓
upload
↓
delete both files

Always ensure directory exists:

mkdir(tempDir, { recursive: true })
13. Protecting the Server

Important safeguards when processing video:

Timeout protection
kill ffmpeg after 2 minutes

Prevents hung processes.

Cleanup

Always delete temp files:

finally {
  unlink(input)
  unlink(output)
}

Prevents disk overflow.

